    {
      "id": "1a79558d329688c5b87d6f65dca69b995e84c34f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-01-11 18:02:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\nThis looks okay for 2.12 since no one uses this API yet. Now if we start moving to rhashtables then this is not enough to prevent build breakage. The question for 2.13 is do we care? RHEL7, SLES12X and Ubuntu all support rhashtables. Its RHEL6 and SLES11 that doesn't. I add Peter Jones to chime in on this. Note I haven't seen platforms actual build for a while.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "bdfc8424bef719ea5a22411168b182b02880d96c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 247,
        "name": "Peter Jones",
        "email": "pjones@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pjones"
      },
      "date": "2019-01-11 19:01:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI don't think that we need to concern ourselves with such old distros for 2.13. People will still be using them of course, but just not with such a current release",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
